06696nam a22008655i 9789814414203DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t19971997si     fo  d z      eng d  a97898144142037 a10.1355/97898144142032doi  a(DE-B1597)492305  a(OCoLC)1100441370  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG 7aBUS0320002bisacsh00aAsia Pacific Air Transport :bChallenges and Policy Reforms /ced. by Christopher Findlay, Lin Sien Chia, Karmjit Singh. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[1997] 4c©1997  a1 online resource (306 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tTables -- tAppendices -- tPreface -- tAuthors -- tIntroduction -- tPart One: Overview -- t1. Challenges and opportunities for Asian airlines and governments -- tPart Two: Policy Issues -- t2. Air traffic congestion and infrastructure development in the Pacific Asia region -- t3. Privatisation in Asia Pacific aviation -- t4. Impediments to liberalisation in Asia Pacific international aviation -- t5. Multiple designation policy in Korea -- t6. Multiple designation policy in Australia -- t7. Air transport policy in Japan: limited competition under regulation -- tPart Three: Regional Initiatives -- t8. The Asia Pacific airline industry: prospects for multilateral liberalisation -- t9. Canada-US Open Skies -- t10. Developments in the European Union: lessons for the Pacific Asia region -- t11 . Flying towards a single aviation market across the Tasman -- tGlossary -- tAcronyms -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt is often taken as a simple truth that the Civil War and the Thirteenth Amendment to the Constitution ended slavery in the United States. In the Southwest, however, two coercive labor systems, debt peonage—in which a debtor negotiated a relationship of servitude, often lifelong, to a creditor—and Indian captivity, not only outlived the Civil War but prompted a new struggle to define freedom and bondage in the United States.In Borderlands of Slavery, William S. Kiser presents a comprehensive history of debt peonage and Indian captivity in the territory of New Mexico after the Civil War. It begins in the early 1700s with the development of Indian slavery through slave raiding and fictive kinship. By the early 1800s, debt peonage had emerged as a secondary form of coerced servitude in the Southwest, augmenting Indian slavery to meet increasing demand for labor. While indigenous captivity has received considerable scholarly attention, the widespread practice of debt peonage has been largely ignored. Kiser makes the case that these two intertwined systems were of not just regional but also national importance and must be understood within the context of antebellum slavery, the Civil War, emancipation, and Reconstruction.Kiser argues that the struggle over Indian captivity and debt peonage in the Southwest helped both to broaden the public understanding of forced servitude in post-Civil War America and to expand political and judicial philosophy regarding free labor in the reunified republic. Borderlands of Slavery emphasizes the lasting legacies of captivity and peonage in Southwestern culture and society as well as in the coercive African American labor regimes in the Jim Crow South that persevered into the early twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Infrastructure.2bisacsh1 aBowen, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButton, Kenneth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChia, Lin Sien, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDempsey, Paul Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc